<subSubSection box="[151,843,1590,1617]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,843,1590,1617]" box="[151,843,1590,1617]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,843,1590,1617]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,843,1590,1617]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt" authorityYear="2021" box="[207,310,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matrona">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,310,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">matrona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (formerly the 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[574,752,1590,1617]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">nigrimaculella</emphasis>
group)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1663,2013]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
Externally, species possess various patterns of the forewing (
<figureCitation box="[835,904,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,437,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-140@6.[152,1435,417,1913]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. Diagnostic tool for species identification of the Pseudopostega matrona group and its distribution. 2, pictorial tool for species differentiation; 3, known distribution (map base, courtesy of T. Patterson, USA)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554950/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), however, usually they have dark markings on the costal margin of the forewing; snow white frontal tuft. In the male genitalia, the uncus is comprised of two distinctive, but variously shaped lateral lobes (see 
<figureCitation box="[682,749,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,437,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-140@6.[152,1435,417,1913]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. Diagnostic tool for species identification of the Pseudopostega matrona group and its distribution. 2, pictorial tool for species differentiation; 3, known distribution (map base, courtesy of T. Patterson, USA)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554950/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); the gnathos is an inverted V-shape; the valva with a unique, short, oval-shaped, median process (
<figureCitation box="[562,631,1771,1797]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,437,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-140@6.[152,1435,417,1913]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. Diagnostic tool for species identification of the Pseudopostega matrona group and its distribution. 2, pictorial tool for species differentiation; 3, known distribution (map base, courtesy of T. Patterson, USA)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554950/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); and the vinculum with a distinctive, elaborate, basally widened juxta. Females are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1663,2013]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
From other groups of Oriental (or Neotropical) 
<taxonomicName box="[724,894,1843,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[724,894,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Pseudopostega</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt" authorityYear="2021" box="[946,1040,1843,1868]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matrona">
<emphasis box="[946,1040,1843,1868]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">matrona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is easily distinguished by the unique median process of valva in the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[756,825,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,437,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-140@6.[152,1435,417,1913]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. Diagnostic tool for species identification of the Pseudopostega matrona group and its distribution. 2, pictorial tool for species differentiation; 3, known distribution (map base, courtesy of T. Patterson, USA)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554950/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1663,2013]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
Distribution. Currently the group is comprised of two Oriental species from 
<collectingCountry box="[1067,1167,1915,1941]" name="Thailand" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and one Mediterranean species described below (
<figureCitation box="[437,505,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–3" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,437,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-140@6.[152,1435,417,1913]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 2–3. Diagnostic tool for species identification of the Pseudopostega matrona group and its distribution. 2, pictorial tool for species differentiation; 3, known distribution (map base, courtesy of T. Patterson, USA)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554950/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="347" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1663,2013]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,393]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="347" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
Remarks. The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[363,528,1987,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrimaculella">
<emphasis box="[363,528,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">nigrimaculella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group was erected in the taxonomic revision of the Oriental 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1893" box="[1207,1347,1987,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Opostegidae</taxonomicName>
(Puplesis and Robinson 1999) based on two white-colored species described from 
<collectingCountry box="[1012,1116,151,177]" name="Thailand" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">Thailand</collectingCountry>
: one possessing a tiny black costal spot on the forewing and another without a spot. The diminutive name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[1044,1209,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrimaculella">
<emphasis box="[1044,1209,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">nigrimaculella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[219,291,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">nigrus</emphasis>
(black) and 
<emphasis box="[437,519,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">macula</emphasis>
(a spot, stain) in reference to a black spot on the forewing of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[1235,1429,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrimaculella">
<emphasis box="[1235,1429,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">P. nigrimaculella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Because of the discovery of 
<taxonomicName authority="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt, 2021" authorityName="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt" authorityYear="2021" box="[473,595,259,284]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matrona" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[473,595,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">P. matrona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[603,693,259,285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, described below, the concept of the species group was redefined. Within the species group, 
<taxonomicName authority="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt, 2021" authorityName="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt" authorityYear="2021" box="[454,578,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matrona" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[454,578,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">P. matrona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[587,677,295,321]" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is characterized by very distinctive external and internal (genital) characters but has no spot on the forewing. Because of the discovery of 
<taxonomicName authority="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt, 2021" authorityName="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt" authorityYear="2021" box="[945,1065,331,356]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matrona" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[945,1065,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">P. matrona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1071,1159,331,357]" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, we selected a new name for the species group: the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis &amp; Karsholt" authorityYear="2021" box="[441,712,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matrona">
<emphasis box="[441,712,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="347">Pseudopostega matrona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
